In Java, the == operator checks for reference equality, while the .equals() method checks for value equality.

The == operator checks if the two references point to the same object in memory. If they do, it returns true. If they don't, it returns false.

The .equals() method checks if the values of the two objects are equal. It is defined in the Object class and is overridden in the String class to compare the characters of the strings.

In general, you should use .equals() to compare strings, as it is more reliable and consistent. The == operator can be used to compare strings if you are sure that the strings are not null and that they are interned (i.e., they are the same object in memory).

Here is an example of how to use .equals() to compare strings:

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("The strings are equal.");
} else {
